******
[3]
Date: 24 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Polioeradication website [link on front page; edited]
<http://www.polioeradication.org>

Polio appears to be on the decline in Mogadishu, formerly the epicentre of
the outbreak. However, the virus has spread to 2 new regions in Lower
Shabelle, southern Somalia, and Mudug region, Northeast Somalia. Both areas
were previously unaffected by the current outbreak in the country. This
comes at a time when a nation-wide polio vaccination campaign to be
launched on Sunday, 26 Mar [2006], aims to vaccinate 1.4 million children
in an effort to halt further spread of the virus and protect the gains made
in Mogadishu.
In 2005, 82 percent of the polio cases recorded in Somalia were from
Mogadishu; following repeated vaccination campaigns there, only 3 of the 14
cases reported in 2006 are in the city. The progress made against the
poliovirus in the capital, with its difficult security environment,
indicates that polio outbreak response strategies are starting to take effect.
Both new cases, coming from regions with security-related restrictions,
present a risk to neighbouring countries and threaten the progress made in
Mogadishu. The polio outbreak in Somalia, which occurred in July 2005 with
an importation of poliovirus, has affected a total of 199 children to date.
Public health officials remain optimistic, however, aware that Somalia has
previously stopped polio, even against the backdrop of political
instability that has plagued the country. With repeated vaccination
campaigns that delivered oral polio vaccine to all children under the age
of 5 [years], overcoming serious security challenges, Somalia recorded its
last case of indigenous polio in 2002.
"Somalia has been polio-free before," reminded WHO representative for
Somalia, Dr. Ibrahim Betelmal. "With safe access for our vaccinators and
the support of the community, Somalia can stop polio again." The global
polio eradication strategies of mass and repeated vaccination campaigns
have reduced worldwide incidence of the disease by 99 percent, across a
wide variety of political, financial and cultural contexts.
The additional immunization activities required have stretched the
resources of the 18-year USD 4 billion effort to eradicate polio worldwide.
"To carry out these additional campaigns," UNICEF Representative, Christian
Baslev-Olesen said, "we will need an additional USD 11 million in Somalia
alone." The release of these funds is paramount for supplemental
immunizations activities supported by WHO and UNICEF.
Led by a public-private partnership, the Global Polio Eradication
Initiative has reduced the number of countries with indigenous poliovirus
from 125 to just 4. Outbreaks of imported polio currently affect 8
countries beside Somalia. Health officials warn that until the poliovirus
is eradicated everywhere, all countries run the risk of importations.
--
