[4]
Date: 24 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Polio eradication website [16 Feb 2006 accessed 24 Mar 2006; edited]
<http://www.polioeradication.org/%5Ccontent%5Cgeneral%5COutbreak_UpdatesSOM20060215.asp
.>

Somalia - 23 Feb 2006
Latest case count
-------------
Current situation:
Somalia is the only country in the world with a geographically expanding
polio outbreak. A polio case was recently confirmed in Gedo province, which
borders Kenya. The risk of continued spread -- within the country and
beyond -- remains high. A nationwide immunization campaign with monovalent
oral polio vaccine is currently ongoing, in coordination with neighbouring
countries.
Background:
Somalia, a country plagued by ongoing conflict, insecurity, the lack of a
health infrastructure and low rates of population immunity, is at the top
of the Global Polio Eradication Initiative's list of acute challenges.
Recognizing the threat of poliovirus importations due to polio outbreaks in
nearby Ethiopia, Sudan and Yemen, Somalia had previously conducted three
NIDs before the first polio case of the outbreak in July 2005. These
preventive campaigns have been instrumental in limiting the spread of the
virus following importation.
Response:
Since the start of the outbreak, 6 National Immunization Days (NID) have
been conducted and have limited the geographic spread of the virus. 5 of
these campaigns used the powerful new monovalent oral polio vaccine.
A review of management and operations in the country was conducted in
November [2005] in order to guide action and limit the outbreak. To
overcome the constant constraints of insecurity and inaccessibility, WHO
and UNICEF work in close collaboration with communities and local officials
on the polio eradication effort. The programme employs 198 national and 10
international staff. During immunization campaigns, additional community
members are recruited to assist in vaccination, logistics, social
mobilization and security.
With sufficient funding, additional immunization activities will be
conducted in early 2006 and the outbreak could be stopped by the end of the
1st quarter.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the polio eradication website
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casecount.pdf>, the date
of onset of the most recent confirmed case was 21 Jan 2006, albeit today's
WHO CSR report suggests there are 2 new cases from regions outside of the
capital city (a good map of Somalia with regions is available at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/africa/somalia_pol02.jpg>). It should be
noted that the region of Mudug borders Ethiopia, raising concerns of
possible spread into Ethiopia as well (there were 22 cases of polio
confirmed in Ethiopia in 2005 with date of onset of most recent case 6 Dec
2005 <http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casecount.pdf>). As
transmission has been ongoing in Somalia since July 2005, it is now 8
months into re-established transmission related to the importation. There
were no cases of polio reported in Somalia during 2003 and 2004. This
current situation is disheartening, and of concern given the political and
civil unrest in the country. - Mod.MPP]
